title: Helper Application
content:
I need to download the helper application to be able to download adobe.

The instructions below are for Firefox 3.0. This version does not match. Please help

To be able to download, add Adobe's site to the list of "allowed sites" in Firefox: 

       On the Tools menu, select Options; click the Content icon        Check the "Block pop-up windows" box, then the Exceptions button        On the "Allowed Sites - Popup" window, enter www.adobe.com in the Address box and click Allow, then Close.    On the Tools menu, select Add-ons; click the "Get Extensions" link in the lower right corner of the popup window.    On the Add-ons page, select Plugins from the menu on the left.    Click the green Install Now button that appears under the Acrobat Reader header.    Adobe's Reader page is displayed. Follow the instructions for downloading the correct version.    A "Software Installation" box is displayed; click Install Now.

title: Can no longer open email attachments without downloading
content:
With Firefox on Debian 11 Linux, i used to be able to open email attachments without downloading them. Since installing Firefox 102.3.0 ESR this is no longer possible. I have tried the various possibilities as set out in

https://support.mozilla.org/en-US/kb/change-firefox-behavior-when-open-file#w_what-should-firefox-do-with-this-file-prompt

without any success. Whatever I do, Firefox insists on downloading attachments.

This situation causes a lot of frustration. A lot of time is now taken up in accessing the attachments in the Downloads folder and then opening them with appropriate software.

I understand from other messages that Firefox is unlikely to fix this problem.

What can I do ? Practically all other browsers available for Linux users are based on Chrome or Chromium, neither of which allow opening of attachments before downloading.

I wonder whether an email client such as Thunderbird would open attachments without downloading. Does anyone have experience with the current release of Thunderbird ?
